    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-01-10T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-01-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="339"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d339">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">832.01/29</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Chief of the Division of the American
                        Republics</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Duggan</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Legal Adviser</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hachworth</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-01-10">January 10,
                            1938</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Mr. Hackworth</hi>: Summarizing, may I inquire whether the
                    situation is that recognition, however accorded, is required in cases where a
                    recognized government has been ousted by a <hi rend="italic">coup d’état</hi> or
                    revolution and a new régime set up contrary to constitutional methods; but that
                    recognition is not required when the government itself has executed a <hi
                        rend="italic">coup d’état</hi>, displacing a constitution by a new one, or
                    abrogating it altogether.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Laurence Duggan</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
